{"/service/ndnp/sdhi/batch_sdhi_ibiza_ver01/data/sn95076623/00279522722/1921032401/0923.xml":{"full_text":"P:\ntefr\nU\nGo to\nTHE PIONEER-REVIEW\nContinuing1\nThe Philip Weekly Review\nand\nThe Pioneer\nA legal weekly newspaper pub\nlished every Thursday afternoon\nat its office on North Center St.,\nPhilip* South Dakota.\nEntered as seeond class matter\nOB August\n2, 1907, at the postoffice\nat Philip, S. D., under the Act of\nCog-ress of arch 3, 1879.\nCARLSON GOFF, Publishers\nJ. B. GOFF, Editor\nC. A. CARLSON, Business- Mgr.\nPACKER HEAD IS CHEERFUL\nWhatever we may think of the\nfmeking industry, it must not be\nforgotten that the history of the\npast fifteen months should lead us\nto tempere at least in some res\npects much\\that we have said ab\noujt them. We shall never believe\nthat the packers have not in times\npast exerted a large influence in\nshaping the price of livestock, tho\nwe are not as certain as we once\nwere that this has been to the dis\nadvantage of the producer.\nAnother thing is certain the\npackers could not control the sit\nuation or maintain the prices of\ntheir own products when prices\nstarted to crash, and they have\nlost heavily as has everyone else\nduring the past year. Yet they are\nWHEELER'S\nPaint and Muresco\nLubercating Oils\nKerosene and Gasoline\nHardware\nA Line of Good Tools\nBarb wire, Nails and Machinery\nA few slightly damaged A A A\nauto chains per set\nLook over your machinery and\norder repairs needed at once\nG.G.\n6\n\u00a7y\nhopeful of the future,not only in\ntheir own particular industry, but\nin the business \\tforld generally.\nJ. Ogden Armour puts this hope\nfullness in the following cheerful\nlanguage in a recent annual report\nof his company:\n\"At this turn in the road we\nhave reason to take heart. As a\nnation, we have broken all prece\ndents\u2014there has been no financial\npanic, despite a rapid decline in\nprices. This decline is putting us\non a firmer footing. With courage [Pow\nor channels of trade and restore\nthe true ratio of prices one to\nward~ another, we shall step upon\nthe threshold of a new era\u2014a fut\nure of upbuilding and steady pro\ngress.\n\"Nothing can cheat us out of\na quick return of prosperity but\nour own lack of faith. And in the\nfinal test, America never loses its\nfaith.\nOTTTJMWA NEWS\nThere si no way to make a gar\nden spake look as attractive as a\nseed catalogue.\nMrs. J. T. Singleton was a guest\nof Mrs. W. S. Shoun Friday.\nSunday was not only a stormy\nday but one filled with disappoint\nments as well. Mr. and Mrs. H. B.\nHudson had planned on a picnic\ndinner at their plice, with the ob\nject in view of organizing and el\necting officers for the Everybody's\nPicnic. Down at Ottumwa a few\nof the high rollers were planning\non a trip to the Bad Lands, and\nat the Manalia school house the\nDoes Your Money Help\nYour Community?\nYou who demand better streets, better\niidewalks, better police and fire protec\ntion\u2014are you doing your part towards\nsuch improvement? Not if you send\nmoney out of town\u2014money that would\nhave just as much buying power\nat home.\nEvery nickel you send away makes\nyour community so much poorer, fcfr\nthe people who receive it do not r$\u00bb\ninvest it here. That money goes for\nthe development of another com*\nmunity or city.\nTRADE\nwAi home\nL.X3iiS\nPatronize our home\nmerchants whenever\npossible and you wil\ndo one of your fore\nmost duties to you|\ncommunity.\nllill!I.\nin! I\nniii !ilii\n//1i,,i!l!!l\nrevivals, were to close with two\nservices at 10 o'clock and at two\n8J o'clcok respectively, but the weath\nSp\u00a7 er man decided to take his inning\ni#j which made it necessary to post\npone everything else.\nIt would be a joke on the demo\ncratic party if the Washington\nball team were to win a pennant\nunder the new administration.\nFred Mains, C. D. Hoover, C.\nW. Phillips and afew others have\ntried to commence farming. Why\n\u2022V* all this hurry? We have been prom\nised seed time and harvest.\nx\u00aej| Waiting for the rent hog 1 re\nduce rents while there are plenty\nEp of tenants is like waiting\nfor\nodrinary hog to stop eating while\n|y there is plenty of food in the\nIP trough.\nGermans am now s bing:\nIp* \"Right is being trodden by\nmight.\" They should remember\nthe days when they were grinding\njj^ Belgium under their heels and\nchanting in their thick Teuton\njlr* tongue that might was right\nSome high brow once si mg\nthis: \"In the spring a young girls\nJy fancy lightly turns to clothes\nthat's all.\" And I would say the\nsame is true in summer and in\nwinter and in fall.\nThirteen thousand\nto take our losses, to open again'*ze that the mothers of these thir-\nan\nAn, can\n|L mothers of slain soldiers, history\n\u00a7ft tells us are waiting in sorrow and\nhusheu amid the noise of lile for\nthe longest funeral processi n in\nthe world. Of course the thirty-\nI two thousand boys from America\nwho sleep beneath the rocks of\nthe Argonne cemetery, the moth\ni ers of thirteen thousand have call\nede for their sons. So officers and\ntheir assistants have gone to the\nImmortal fields with long lists\nlike roll calls and are silently sep\narating the dead from the dead\nfor the little comfort it may give\nthe mothers who in far too many\ncases gave their all. These moth\ners speak in their mother way the\neloquence of the world Some\nthought they knew what was was\nwhen they watched the trains go\ndown to the ships and the ships\ngo out to sea. We thought we\nknew what poacomeant when the\nboys came home with victorv. But\nwe ,earn more when we\nr(al-\nteen thousand have been only\nwating, while we gloried in war\nor rejoiced in peace for these sil\nnt home comings. Not all of us\nknow what war was or what peace\nmeans. They know best who are\nin the Argonne or came or are\ncoming home for their minion of\nthe recognitions of a better world.\nThe dance given at the home of\nthe Downings Saturday evening\nwas not verey well attended owing\nto\nthe uncertainty of the weather.\nW. S. Shoun again had his neigh\nbors out on Saturday, this time\nfor the purpose of vaccinating his\ncattle.\nHAPPINESS\nI had a little shanty ami I was\nhappy there, with wife and niece\nand auntie, and grandma in her\nchair. I did not owe a shilling,\nupon that small abode, no credit\nors came drilling to dun me up\nthe road. And I was always sav\ning against the day of rain, and\nall the time behaving like some\none safe and sane. My aunt,\nwhose name was Alice was dip\npy as could be she said a costly\nnalace was none too good for me.\n\\nd grandma, in her sweater,\nbacked aunt, and said, \"Tut,tut.\nYou should have something bet\nter\u2014why live in this punk hut?\"\nMy niece endorsed their kicking,\nand nagged all day and buck, for\n^he was tired of sticking in such\ni tawdry shack. With womne thus\nembattled, what can a poor man\nlo? At last they got me rattled\nand all my coin I drew I mortga\nged and I borrowed and biult a\ncostly home, and ever since Tve\nsorrowed, and care has creased my\ndome. I owe the village plumber\nwho plied his art with skill, and\nat the house each comer is some\none with a bill. I \u00a9we the gifted\npainter, whose language freely\nflows. as smoker and (jauinter\npaperhanger, the joiner for his\nbeams, and can hear their clang\nor, at midnight, in my dreams.\nThey all are rude and rantv, and I\ndissolve in tears, when thinking\nof my shanty that knew my youfljj\nyears\u2014Walt NJason.\nThe Story Hour at the Library\nlast Saturday, conducted by Mrs.\nO. M. Culp, was largely attended\nby the boys and girls. After sev\neral Victrola selections were giv\nen the children listened with\ngrowing interest while Mrs. Culp\nread to them from Kazan, occas\nsionally they stopped for a few\nmoments to listen co the Victrola\nbut eagerely listened again to the\nreading. One little girl expressed\nthe general feeling whe.i she safd:\n\"Oh, Mrs. Culp, please do not stop\ni in a real exciting \\dace we can\niaot wait till jiext tiuw,\"\nREAL TURK NOT MONEY MAD\nRecognizes Thera Are Higher Thing*\nin Life Than Practicing Buying\nand Selling.\nThe real Turk, unlike the so-called\nmongrel Turk, does not have to Im\npress his sense of superiority on oth\ners. And, although the latter Is al\nways eager to do business with you,\naccording to Mr. Herbert Gibbons In\nAsia, the real Turk is often quite In\ndifferent.\nSome real Anatolian Turks are mer\nchants nnd sit in the bazaars. But\nthey will not go out of their way to\nmake a sale, and they really do not\ncare whether you buy or not. Often\nthey Ignore strangers sometimes they\nrebuff them. When you meet with\nthis type in the bazaars where all the\nJews and Gentiles are hard after your\nmoney, it is like a dash ot cold wa\nter in your face.\nOnce In a little open shop I saw a\nrug that attracted me. I started to\nenter, but the crourhed figure on the\nmat put out a long-fingered left hand,\ngrasped tirmly my ankle, and removed\nmy foot outside the threshold. I\nthought there must be some supersti\ntion about which foot went first so\nI\ntried the other. The same left hand\nproved again its strength. All the\nwhile the merchant did not speak or\n\"took tip. His right hand was string\ning beads, and he was smoking a nar\nglle.\nHe \\fmply if!d not want to bother\nwith me. and my shoe told him that\nI was a franeea (European). Later\nV to know that old bird, and we\niaiu'hed over stories together. Rut\nhe never naked me to buy anything,\nund did not want to risk his friend\nship by making a seeond try for the\nme. There are more important things\n!n life \u00bbh\u00bbn buying and selling.\n\"SQUEEZE\" POPULAR IN CHINA\nWhat the Western World Calls \"Graft\"\nIs Practiced by All Classes In\nThat Country.\nOne trait firmly Imbedded In the\nChinese character which the foreign\nhusiness man and the housewife both\nhave to contend with Is the weakness\nfor \"squeeze.\" It Is said by foreigners\nthat the Chinese merchant, coolie,\npolitician, fisherman, chauffeur and\nbeggar would rather make $1 by\n\"squeeze\" than $10 by the same\namount of brain work or manual la\nbor.\nSqueeze Is Chinese for graft. It Is\na word In that International Far F*n\u00abt\nern tongue known as pidgin-English.\nRut squeeze Is something more than\ngraft. Its political phase might be\ntermed graft, and that form of squeeze\nla what makes the military governors\nof the provinces nnd the politicians of\nPeking and Canton so fat. Most Chi\nnese politicians would have been ac\nceptable In the eyes of Julius Caesar,\nand squeeze Is the reason for some of\nthe corpulence in China.\nSqueeze Is the Chinese translation\nof \"as much as the traffic will bear.\"\nIt Is a factor In Chinese business, as\nmuch as supply and demand, or profit\nand loss.\nTapestry In History.\nDaring the Italian Renatssan*#\nart developed In subtle treatment of\ncolor and shading, and Flemish tap\nestry reached its height of artistic per\nfection In the magnificent pieces from\ncartoons by Raphael and other Ital\nian masters.\nRoyalty supported the Industry at\nthis period. Incidents of history were\nwoven into design with threads of\ngold and silver, and even Jewels. Oth\ners were mellowed by soft colorings of\nwool, with their high lights supplied\nby silken threads. The dyes, often as\ncostly as the gold and silver, have\nteeld their colors for centuries, and It\nhas been beyond the modern chemist\nto solve their alchemy. No such col\nors can be produced today, nor none\nfhat are so unfading. When tapestry\nmaking waned In Brussels. Fnince de\nv'eleped\nfhe\nart, and under Henry IV\nsnd Louis XIV the Gobelins were\nfamed for their perfectloa Of work\nmanship and color.\nAn Apple a Day.\n\"They tell us,\" said Mr. Bllltops,\n'that an apple a day keeps the doctor\niway, and I guess that Is so I am\nmre that an apple a night promotes\n\u00bbound and restful slumber.\n\"We keep our apples In the icebox.\nThe last thing that Mrs. Bllltops, ever\nhoughtful Mrs. Bllltops, does in mak\nng her rounds before retiring for the\nlight is to get an apple out of the Ice\nbox and place It, with a fruit knife,\nto the dining-room table for me.\n\"Nightly the last th-ng I do before\nolng to bed Is to go out into the din\nIng room, seat myself comfortably,\nand eat that apple: leisurely. I find It\npool and refreshing In every war\nagreeable: and having eates it I turn\nIn and sleep delightfully.\n\"An apple a day keeps the doctor\naway. An apple at night makes you\nsleep right.\"\nExclusive Organization,\nThough legendarlly reputed to be\nmore then 1,000 years old, the Order\nof the Thistle was founded by James\nII In lfi87. After the revolution, says\nthe I.ondon Star, It fell Into desue\ntude, but was revived by Queen Anne\nIn 1703. The chapel of the order, In\nSt Giles* cathedral, where the king\nattended service on Sunday,\nwas\nvfctli Mfc*\nd\\i\nas\nIS YOUR LAND\nan Oil Structure\nThe main requisites\nSTATE POTATO EXCHANGE\nBrookings, S D.\u2014A constant to\ntal of about 20 cents per hundred\nweight, or 12 cents per bushel is\nestimated as the probable cost of\nselling South Dakota potatoes thru\na central potato exchange. These\nfigures have been arrived at by\nthe potato marketing committee\nof the South Dakota Potato Grow\ner's Association, of which H. B.\nMcKibbon, White, is chairman.\nPlans for the organization of a\nstate potato-exchange will be pre\nsented by the committee at a meet\ning of all who are interested at\nWatertown, Friday, March 25th.\nUnder this plan local association\nwould be formed with local mana\ngers to look after the grading, the\nbagging and loading of the crop.\nGrowers uniting with the associa\ntion would agree to ship their\ncommercial crop thruogh the as\nsociation and as a guarantee give\na non-interest bearing promisory\nnote for $100, the guarantee being\ngiven to assure enough business\nA central exchange composed of\nThey\nnot\ncommenced until 1009.\nThe Thistle Is one of the most ex\nclusive orders. Its only members b#\nIng the king and 16 knights. The motto\nof the order la: **Wha\ndaur\nmeddle\n4\nJ,\nHow about that piece you can buy for a song? Or that\nthat piece you are about to sell? Do you know that some of\nthe most eminent geologists of the northwest worked several\nmonths iff South Dakota last year and that many of the larger\ncompanies are figuring on doing big development in South Da\nkota this year? Do yon want some inside dope on the Oil Busi\nness in this state?\nOIL MAP of SO. DAK.\nWill Tell You\nfor a productive\nfeatures of the structures of South Dakota, their location, the\npossible oil-bearing sands and their number, the approximate\ndrilling dpths, compiled and drawn by Howard P. Manning after\na year's investigation of the possible oil-bearing territory of\nSouth Dakota. Better sit down and order yourself one right\nnow,\nthere are'only a few of these maps in print. Order from\nH, P. UANNiNG, FAITH, SOUTH DAKOTA\nPRICE $1.00, POSTPAID\nMAY BE ORGANIZED SOON\nto maintain the association. The data gathered the past 4 years\nnote would be cancelled after de- it is found that the growers of\nlivery of the crop, upon fulfillment\nof the contract.\nTo the Farmers\nand Others\nIfa* cannot sell your crops unless men are working.\nMen cannot work unless you buy the things they produce.\nIf ytm buy clothing, undewear, hats, stockings, farm imple\nments and household articles you give employment to fac\u00ad\nON\noil field, the general\na general manager and sales force\nwrould also be provided. Local as\nsociations would bind themselves\nto ship al their products through\nthe central exchange. This associa\ntion would have complete charge\nof the selling of the crop. As soon\nas the potatoes were loaded into\ncars the local manager would no\ntify the central exchange of the\nkind and amount in each car. The\ncentral exchange would then is\nsue shipping instructions and look\nafter the sales and collections.\nThe price would be based on the\naverage of the day's pool, as all\npotatoes shipped from the various\nlocals would be posted each day.\nThe central exchange would then\nadvance 80 per cent of the price\nto the local manager for the pota\ntoes shipped from his local and as\nsoon as the returns were in 10 per\ncent more jvouldbe advanced and\nthe other 10 per cent retained as\nselling charges. The total cost to\nthe grower should be about as fol\nlows: 10 cents per hundredweight\nto the central selling agency, plus\nthe cost of Istoding at the shipping\npoint, which at most rarely ex\nceeds another 10 cents per hund\nredweight. This would make a\ntotal of 20 cents per hundred wei\nght or 12 cents per bushel. From\nSouth Dakota, under the present\nsystem of marketing, are paying\nmuch more than this figure.\ntory worker\u00ae who produce thaae thing* railroad workers\nwho trasport them clerks and stockkeepers, miners who\nsupply coal to run the plants and railroads, and countless\nothers\u2014all users of farm products.\nThey cannot eat bread, mscle of your wheat, wear clothing\nmade of your wool, cannot consumer your corn, oats els.,\nunless they are working.\ncannot work unless you keep buying-. If you stop\n\u2014business stops. Your business and their business.\nYou can't scSI crops to\"bread line\" man.\nThis is the greatest country on earth and will contiqe to do\nKeep off buying\u2014carefally\u2014but\nbusiness\u2014hut\u2014you can give it had bump unless you keep\nbuying the things you\nWhen in need of Clothing come to Pierre and see the oldreliar\nble, TpNY CLOTHING, CO., Pierre South Dakota.\nbuying\ns*--\nTONY CLOTHING CO\n'i .\"v \u00abV\u2022 V9- V\"- \u00bb,V\n'\u2022f-S'\nt'","height":"27471","width":"19302"}}
